id,text,target
bio_graph_0000024,"On a remote volcanic island, there are 7 species labeled A, B, C, D, E, F, and G.
adult species form a directed feeding network.

Biologists established the following rules:
- each specie preys on exactly 2 distinct others.
- each specie is targeted by exactly 3 others.
- no species preys on itself.
- no two species prey on each other.
- the full ecosystem must be strongly connected.

Observed relationships:
- A preys on B.
- B preys on C.
- C preys on D.
- D preys on A.
- F preys on C.
- G preys on F.

Determine whether a valid completion exists. If it does, provide one valid completion. If it does not, identify the contradiction.",0
bio_graph_0000108,"Within an isolated nutrient-exchange habitat, there are 10 organisms labeled A, B, C, D, E, F, G, H, I, and J. field researchers documented a stable directed interaction structure. The system obeys the following rules: each organism has directed outgoing interactions toward exactly 3 distinct others; each organism receives directed input from exactly 1 others; no organism interacts with itself; no directed interaction is reciprocated; the full interaction system must be strongly connected; every species must lie on at least one directed cycle. Field observations additionally record that A extracts nutrients from B; B extracts nutrients from C; C extracts nutrients from D; D extracts nutrients from A; I extracts nutrients from C; J extracts nutrients from I. Determine whether a valid completion exists. If it does, provide one valid completion. If it does not, identify the contradiction.",0
bio_graph_0000057,"In a sealed subterranean habitat, there are 8 species labeled A, B, C, D, E, F, G, and H.
researchers observed a directed nutrient-dependency network among six to ten species.

Biologists established the following rules:
- each specie has directed outgoing interactions toward exactly 1 distinct others.
- each specie receives directed input from exactly 2 others.
- no organism interacts with itself.
- no directed interaction is reciprocated.
- the full nutrient network must be strongly connected.
- every species must lie on at least one directed cycle.

Observed relationships:
- A draws nutrients from B.
- B draws nutrients from C.
- C draws nutrients from D.
- D draws nutrients from A.
- G draws nutrients from C.
- H draws nutrients from G.

Determine whether a valid completion exists. If it does, provide one valid completion. If it does not, identify the contradiction.",0
bio_graph_0000019,"Within an isolated nutrient-exchange habitat, there are 8 organisms labeled A, B, C, D, E, F, G, and H. field researchers documented a stable directed interaction structure. The system obeys the following rules: each organism has directed outgoing interactions toward exactly 3 distinct others; each organism receives directed input from exactly 1 others; no organism interacts with itself; no directed interaction is reciprocated; the full interaction system must be strongly connected; every species must lie on at least one directed cycle. Field observations additionally record that A extracts nutrients from B; B extracts nutrients from C; C extracts nutrients from D; D extracts nutrients from A; G extracts nutrients from C; H extracts nutrients from G. Can the partial observations be extended to a full valid system? Give a witness if possible, otherwise prove impossibility.",0
bio_graph_0000164,"Inside a sealed ecological basin, there are 9 organisms labeled A, B, C, D, E, F, G, H, and I.
field researchers documented a stable directed interaction structure.

Biologists established the following rules:
- each organism has directed outgoing interactions toward exactly 2 distinct others.
- each organism receives directed input from exactly 1 others.
- no organism interacts with itself.
- the full interaction system must be strongly connected.

Observed relationships:
- A extracts nutrients from B.
- B extracts nutrients from C.
- C extracts nutrients from D.
- D extracts nutrients from A.
- H extracts nutrients from C.
- I extracts nutrients from H.

Can the partial observations be extended to a full valid system? Give a witness if possible, otherwise prove impossibility.",0
bio_graph_0000035,"In a sealed marsh habitat, there are 6 species labeled A, B, C, D, E, and F. biologists recorded a regular feeding network among the adult species. The system obeys the following rules: each specie preys on exactly 2 distinct others; each specie is targeted by exactly 1 others; no species preys on itself; no two species prey on each other. Field observations additionally record that A preys on B; B preys on C; C preys on D; D preys on A; E preys on C; F preys on E. Is a full interaction network satisfying all rules possible? If yes, construct one. If no, explain why not.",0
bio_graph_0000011,"Within an isolated cave ecosystem, there are 7 species labeled A, B, C, D, E, F, and G. the adult population participates in a closed nutrient-exchange structure. The system obeys the following rules: each specie has directed outgoing interactions toward exactly 3 distinct others; each specie receives directed input from exactly 2 others; no organism interacts with itself; no directed interaction is reciprocated; the full nutrient network must be strongly connected; every species must lie on at least one directed cycle. Field observations additionally record that A draws nutrients from B; B draws nutrients from C; C draws nutrients from D; D draws nutrients from A; F draws nutrients from C; G draws nutrients from F. Can the partial observations be extended to a full valid system? Give a witness if possible, otherwise prove impossibility.",0
bio_graph_0000056,"Within an isolated cave ecosystem, there are 7 species labeled A, B, C, D, E, F, and G. biologists modeled the colony as a directed nutrient-flow network. The system obeys the following rules: each specie has directed outgoing interactions toward exactly 2 distinct others; each specie receives directed input from exactly 3 others; no organism interacts with itself; no directed interaction is reciprocated. Field observations additionally record that A draws nutrients from B; B draws nutrients from C; C draws nutrients from D; D draws nutrients from A; F draws nutrients from C; G draws nutrients from F. Can the partial observations be extended to a full valid system? Give a witness if possible, otherwise prove impossibility.",0
